<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yerin, Stepashin Discuss Anti-Crime Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yerin, Stepashin Discuss Anti-Crime Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106135294 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1100 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer Mikhail Zotov] A news conference took 
place in the government building on Krasnaya Presnya in Moscow 
today. Its theme was the intensification of the fight against 
crime which the power ministries are planning in the near future. 
  Vladimir Rubanov, deputy secretary of the Security Council, 
said that the benefit gained from the additional anti-crime 
measures, calculated according to UN methods, should be about 10 
trillion rubles. Five trillion rubles will be spent on the 
measures themselves, and the Security Council will oversee the 
conduct of the campaign. 
  Aleksey Ilyushenko, acting procurator general, said that the 
procuracy would coordinate this work. In view of the provisions 
of the draft law on the fight against crime which permit the 
Interior Ministry to introduce agents into commercial structure, 
to create sham firms, and to work with securities, journalists 
raised the question of corruption. Viktor Yerin replied to this: 
  [Begin Yerin recording] We have special structural units 
which directly and on their own initiative engage in operational 
work among their own personnel, revealing unscrupulous people. 
[end recording] 
  [Zotov] And although Viktor Yerin considers that one must 
not 
violate the law oneself while fighting illegality, the 
participants in the news conference on intensifying the fight 
against crime were unanimously of the opinion that if the 
legislation was not in accord with the necessary measures to 
combat crime, it must be changed. 
  Sergey Stepashin, director of the Federal 
Counter-Intelligence Service, pointed out to those assembled 
that the counter-intelligence service was restoring its 
investigative apparatus and that about 800 experienced personnel 
had already returned. 
  [Begin Stepashin recording] The president gave the go-ahead 
and draft decrees are now being prepared by [word indistinct] 
together with us, and these decrees on creating a directorate of 
active operations will be signed, most likely next week. It is 
rather broader than the Vympel group. It will be a directorate 
not only of the central apparatus but will also operate in a 
number of regions, in particular in St. Petersburg, in 
Krasnodar, in Yekaterinburg, in Novosibirsk, and in Murmansk. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

