<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   FCIS Creates Division To Fight Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FCIS Creates Division To Fight Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306100794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0938 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1306100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By CRIME-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 13 TASS -- The Federal 
Counterintelligence Service (FCIS) is setting up an active 
operations division to step up struggle against crime, FCIS 
director Sergey Stepashin said at a news conference at the 
government building here on Monday. 
  The division will be established not only at the central 
office. It will also have its branches in big Russian cities, 
including Moscow, St. Petersburg and Novosibirsk. 
  According to the director, these changes are provided for by 
the federal programme for stepping up struggle against crime for 
1994-1995. The FCIS is vested with new, but, in actual fact, 
old forgotten functions, including the return of investigative 
bodies. 
  In the near future, some 700-800 investigators having 
experience of work in security bodies will get down to work at 
the service. 
  In Stepashin's opinion, clear-cut and efficient cooperation 
between his service, on the one hand, and the law enforcement 
bodies, the security service of banks, currency exchange points, 
tax investigation service and, if need be, the president's 
security service as well as other interested structures, on the 
other, will help to implement successfully the federal programme 
for stepping up struggle against crime. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

