<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk, Radetskyy Hold Conference on Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk, Radetskyy Hold Conference on Armed Forces </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1006133894 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 9 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1006133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The Commander in Chief Calls a </F>
Conference"] 
  [Text] A two-day operational conference with the 
leadership of Ukraine's executive power structures was held 
under the chairmanship of supreme commander in chief of 
Ukraine's Armed Forces Ukraine's President Leonid Kravchuk. The 
main task of the conference was to deepen the knowledge of 
representatives of the state administration in questions of the 
military building and strengthening of the country's defense 
capability. As reported by the Press Service of the Ministry of 
Defense, the Ukrainian president pointed out in his speech that 
every leader must find and clearly comprehend his place and role 
in the system of state security. Ukraine's Armed Forces and the 
state apparatus must be constantly ready to defend Ukraine. its 
sovereignty, and territorial integrity -- this is the demand of 
our time. 
  At the same time, Leonid Kravchuk stressed that political 
passions, which presently rage in Ukraine, must remain outside 
the Army, whose main task is to maintain the state's combat 
readiness and inviolability of its borders. 
  The Ukrainian president drew the audience's particular 
attention to the need to make every effort in order to raise the 
authority of the military service and to elaborate a package of 
legislative acts, which would speed up the army's transition to 
the contractual basis of recruitment. 
  Ukraine's minister of defense Army General Vitaliy Radetskyy 
delivered a speech on the concept of the building and 
development of Ukraine's Armed Forces for the period of up to 
the year 2010. 
  On the second day of the conference, its participants 
visited 
the military training center "Desna," where they examined new 
samples of technology and weapons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

