<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Says Candidates Views on Leader Unclear </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Says Candidates Views on Leader Unclear </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206150394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1441 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Leonid Kravchuk said in the western city 
of Lvov that did not know what the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet's 
Presidium or parliamentary groups thought about the candidates 
for premiership. 
  He emphasized the need to have the nominations thoroughly 
discussed and a final choice made. 
  Sources close to the leadership of the Ukrainian parliament 
said that the presidium had decided to ask Vitaly Masol to 
present his program. 
  He was nominated for premiership by Kravchuk. Prime minister 
before 1992, Masol was pensioned off. 
  Kravchuk said in Lvov he would explain his platform in a 
national radio address late on 13 June, nearly two weeks before 
the presidential elections. 

</TEXT>

