<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reveals Presidential Election Program in Lvov </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reveals Presidential Election Program in Lvov </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206161894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1434 
GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko, </F>
Mikhail Melnik, and Galina Nekrasova] 
  [Excerpts] Lvov, 12 Jun -- Today, for the first time, 
Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk unveiled his program for the 
26 June presidential elections during a working trip to Lvov 
Oblast. 
  At a meeting at Lvov Polytechnic State University with 
representatives of the authorities of the western region of 
Ukraine, businessmen, the intelligentsia, and clergy, Leonid 
Kravchuk spoke of the main tenets of his program. Its main 
thesis is "to strengthen the state and speed up the reforms 
through civic accord." He sees his main task as head of 
government as ensuring that "the economic reforms get going and 
that people begin to live better lives," that Ukraine's state 
construction moves ahead. 
  Speaking of the Crimean problem, Leonid Kravchuk stressed 
that "no matter how events develop, Ukraine will not allow the 
territorial integrity of the state, its unity, to be violated. 
Regardless of what the Supreme Council, the government, the 
president of the Crimean autonomous entity do, everything will 
be done to ensure that events on the peninsula do not spill over 
the bounds of the Constitution of Ukraine. There can be no 
alternative here." [passage omitted] 
  During his trip today Leonid Kravchuk unveiled a monument in 
Lvov's central boulevard to Mikhail Grushevskiy who, in 1917-18, 
was the first president of the Ukrainian People's Republic. 
  The president of Ukraine left for Kiev in the evening. 

</TEXT>

