<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Admits `Possibility' of 2 Official Languages </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Admits `Possibility' of 2 Official Languages </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306113394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1026 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1306113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk, who is one of 
the candidates to the presidential post in the current election 
campaign, admits the possibility of two official languages -- 
Russian and Ukrainian, Interfax-Ukraine reports. This idea is 
set forth in Kravchuk's election program, entitled "Through 
Civic Accord to a Stronger State and Faster Reforms." 
  Observers believe that the recognition of Russian as 
Ukraine's second official language will win him additional votes 
in the predominantly Russian eastern and south-eastern regions. 
  If elected, Kravchuk will work for the adoption of a new 
constitution. He favors a presidential-parliamentary form of 
government which, he says, excludes the monopolization of power 
by one of the authoritative branches. 
  Kravchuk supports the concept of unitary state with a 
well-developed network of local governments and broad economic 
independence of the regions. He also favors a legal settlement 
of relations with Crimea. He comes out for the development of 
the CIS, for a more intensive economic integration of the CIS 
countries and for equitable relations with the neighbors, 
including Russia. 
  Kravchuk attaches great importance to a radical improvement 
of the investment climate and will make efforts to ensure that 
Ukrainian and foreign entrepreneurs be equally interested in 
making investments to the Ukrainian industry. 
  He is planning to accelerate the monetary reform and to 
introduce the internally convertible "hryvna." 
  He favors the idea of lowering the bank rates, separating 
the 
finances of industrial enterprises from the state budget, and 
accelerating privatization under state control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

