<DOCNO> FBIS4-40014 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov113cc_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-113 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Comment on Possible CIS Confederation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Comment on Possible CIS Confederation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1106204094 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1700 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1106204094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" program] </F>
  [Text] Today we have a link-up with Minsk and Kiev. The 
leaders of the two republics have agreed to comment in the 
"Novosti- Plyus" program on the statement made by chairman of 
the Federation Council Vladimir Shumeyko, who suggested that in 
all probability a confederation state will appear on the 
one-sixth of the dry land [former Soviet Union], which in future 
can easily change into a federation. 
  [Myacheslaw Gryb, chairman of the Supreme Soviet of the 
Republic of Belarus] This is at present a rather difficult 
question. In principle, I do not reject a confederative 
structure in any state or group of states. But at present a 
somewhat different principle triumphs in the world. At present, 
it is difficult to find a federative state or group of states 
that would merge on purely federative terms, or confederative 
terms. There are elements of one and the other, and even 
something new is emerging, like in the proposals put forward by 
Kazakhstani President Nursultan Nazarbayev. These contain a new 
proposal on the establishment of a new union. All this deserves 
attention, discussion, and careful examination. But in my view 
the first thing we should do is achieve economic union. This, I 
think, is the most important thing. 
  And meanwhile it is a holiday in Russia. We rejoice in this 
holiday and we send our heart-felt greetings. I convey 
greetings on my own behalf, on behalf of the presidium of the 
Supreme Soviet, and the people of Belarus to the people of 
Russia, the Russian Government, and the President of the Russian 
Federation, Boris Nikolayevich Yeltsin, on the occasion of this 
holiday, and wish them all the best on their road of 
independence. 
  [Ukraine President Leonid Kravchuk] First of all I would 
like 
to convey greetings to the peoples of the Russian Federation on 
their national holiday. I would like to take this opportunity 
to wish success, happiness, well-being, and prosperity to all 
the peoples of the multi-ethnic Russia, to our closest neighbor 
and, shall I say, kinsman. 
  Another important aspect for all of us is that the 
proclamation of Russia's independence became a starting point 
for the proclamation of independence of other states. I recall 
that as soon as the Russian parliament adopted the declaration 
of independence, Ukraine, and later other states of the former 
Soviet Union, adopted their own declarations of independence. 
Therefore both in time and in geographical terms, and in any 
other imaginable way, this Russian independence holiday is 
related to the independence of other peoples and states. 
  For me, independence is the right to resolve independently 
those issues that every people, every state has to resolve for 
itself. 
  At present we and Russia are at a very crucial stage. I 
would describe it as a singularly important stage. We have 
begun drawing up a treaty of friendship, cooperation and 
partnership. A basis for this treaty is already in existence. 
We ought to resolve those issues that can, shall I say, 
complicate the signing and adoption of this most important 
document between the two peoples and state. One such is the 
problem of the Black Sea Fleet. We are making very difficult 
step, but they are still steps forward. That's what I would 
like to say. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

