<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comment on EAU, Russian Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Comment on EAU, Russian Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006164094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1437 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: Compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] President Nazarbayev meeting Friday [10 Jun] in Alma 
Ata [Almaty] with the visiting Estonian President Lennart Meri 
said that the creation of a Euro-Asian union (EAU) does not 
envisage the restoration of the former Soviet Union. He said 
there are such fears since some politicians support the idea in 
their statements. This would be a great tragedy and would bring 
about great troubles and more bloodshed. 
  Nazarbayev said that the EAU provides for civilized 
relations 
with the non-members. The Union is open for membership of not 
solely members of the Commonwealth of Independent States. The 
president said that China showed a keen interests to the idea. 
  For his part, Lennart Meri said that Estonia was interested 
in the fact that prevailing on the Euro-Asian mainland would be 
the principles of the democratic development and any threats to 
regional clashes be removed. Proceeding from these positions, 
the Estonian leader said that he warmly welcomes the idea by 
President Nazarbayev about the creation of a Euro-Asian Union. 
  According to Meri, Estonia would not like to fence itself 
from Russia and was prepared to develop the relations. He noted 
there are also problems in relationships with the Russian 
Federation, to which the president attributed the presence of 
2500 servicemen of the former Soviet Army on the Estonian 
territory. Meri hopes, however, that the problem would be 
solved. He said that 31 August when the former Soviet troops 
leave Estonia, Germany and other countries, would an [as 
received] important European event. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

