<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Russian Defense Minister's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Grachev on Readiness </H4>

<F P=102> LD1006111494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0922 
GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006111494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Albert Kochetkov and </F>
Mikhail Shevtsov] 
  [Text] Tbilisi, 10 Jun -- Russian Defense Minister Pavel 
Grachev says that the peace-keeping mission of the Russian 
forces in Abkhazia can start immediately, if the conflicting 
sides agree to this. This will become possible if he receives 
an agreement from the Tbilisi and Gudauta leaders, with whom he 
will hold consultations throughout today. 
  In the first part of the day Grachev discussed this 
possibility with Eduard Shevardnadze, the head of the Georgian 
state, in Tbilisi, and in the afternoon he will hold similar 
talks with Vladislav Ardzinba, the Abkhazian leader, in Gudauta. 
  Incidentally, the minister added that the airborne regiment 
of the Russian Armed Forces, which is stationed in Gudauta and 
which has been officially included in the composition of the CIS 
peace- keeping forces, can be brought in for the beginning of 
the peace- keeping mission. This decision will be in keeping 
with the latest well-known edict by Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin on rendering assistance in settling the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict, and at the same time it does not 
run contrary to the decision of the Federation Council, which 
for the time being is holding back from carrying out a 
peace-keeping mission in the conflict zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

