<DATE1>  12 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kostikov: Democratic Choice Shares Yeltsin's Politics </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kostikov: Democratic Choice Shares Yeltsin's Politics </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206152294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1304 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A 507-strong constituent convention, held Sunday in 
Moscow on the initiative of the Russia's Choice faction in the 
State Duma, declared the creation of "Russia's Democratic Choice 
Party." 
  Co-chairman of the Ukrainian inter-regional bloc 
Grinev-Kuchma and the former deputy-speaker of the Ukrainian 
Supreme Soviet Vladimir Grinev greeted the convention. On 
behalf of the delegates, Anatoliy Chubays, who chaired the 
convention, wished the inter-regional bloc success in the June 
26 presidential elections. 
  President Yeltsin's press secretary Viacheslav Kostikov 
refuses to recognize the new party as "presidential". But in 
terms of politics, he told newsmen, the new party shared much 
with the president and was a product of what Yeltsin started 
back in 1991. 
  According to Kostikov, the Choice's leaders had made no 
false 
moves to make Yeltsin join them. In response to a question from 
Interfax, Kostikov said the convention could yet receive a 
message of greeting from Yeltsin. 
  In Kostikov's view, the new party and Yeltsin ought to keep 
a 
reasonable distance between them. 
  Kostikov would not want to join the party in his capacity of 
a public servant. That would make it more difficult for Yeltsin 
to work, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

