<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Changes To Aid Market Reforms </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Changes To Aid Market Reforms </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406061894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0606 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406061894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS Gennadiy Kulagin] </F>
  [Text] Alma Ata [Almaty] 14 June TASS -- President 
Nursultan Nazarbayev of Kazakhstan has taken new steps to 
accelerate market reforms and pull his republic out of the 
economic crisis. The local press today carries decrees of 
President Nursultan Nazarbayev aimed at major restructuring of 
the Republic's ministries and scrapping some of them altogether. 
  The abolished Ministries of Foreign Economic Relations, 
Industry and Trade will be replaced by one single Ministry of 
Industry and Trade for purposes "of making a more effective use 
of the Republic's production potential and meeting market 
demand, as well as for purposes of entering international 
economic relations as soon as possible." 
  The Ministry of Transport and Communications will take over 
from two other abolished ministries, those of transport and 
communications, which is expected to cut spending on the upkeep 
of state government bodies and streamline their operations. 
  On the other hand, the Ministry of Energy and Fuel resources 
is now divided into two ministries, the Ministry of the Oil and 
Gas Industry and the Ministry of Energy and the Coal Industry to 
ensure a more effective implementation of the state policy in 
the use of the republic's fuel and energy potential as a major 
precondition for accelerating the social and economic 
development of all of its regions. 
  The chairman of the National Bank is given a more 
independent 
status in pursuing the monetary and crediting policy. He will 
no longer be a member of the cabinet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

