<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saudabayev Returns from Istanbul Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saudabayev Returns from Istanbul Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306163494 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Kazakh 1400 GMT 
13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1306163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Kazakh </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Kanat Saudabayev gave a speech last 
Saturday [11 June] at a conference of foreign ministers held in 
Istanbul. He said in particular that Kazakhstan, from the very 
first days of its revived statehood, stands for the 
strengthening of international security and an atmosphere of 
confidence. The Kazakh leadership regards the country's 
participation in North Atlantic cooperation from this viewpoint. 
The preparation of the final documents was held in an 
atmosphere of tense debates, and the Kazakh delegation's 
amendment was introduced. As result, Paragraph 25 of the 
conference statement says: We welcome the fact that the Republic 
of Kazakhstan has joined the Nuclear Weapons Nonproliferation 
Treaty as a state that does not possess such weapons, and highly 
assess Kazakhstan's positive role in the process of dismantling 
the nuclear weapons of the former USSR in conformity with the 
Lisbon protocol. 
  On the same day Kanat Saudabayev met the foreign ministers 
of 
Germany, Greece, Canada, and Turkey. They touched upon topical 
regional and international problems and bilateral relations, as 
well as the further expansion of mutually beneficial trade and 
economic cooperation. The Kazakhstan delegation returned home. 

</TEXT>

