<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pressure To Hold General Strike Grows </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pressure To Hold General Strike Grows </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306161394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0748 
GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1306161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Akimov] </F>
  [Text] Almaty, 13 Jun -- A general strike in protest at the 
uncontrolled increase in fuel prices, which is causing 
production cutbacks, could be unleashed in Kazakhstan. 
Enterprises in the Republic's mining and metallurgical sector 
are in the worst trouble. The staff of these enterprises are 
being sent en masse on vacations for an indefinite period and, 
moreover, many have to go without vacation payments being made. 
The threat of unemployment is hanging over tens of thousands of 
blue- and white-collar staff in the East Kazakhstan Oblast. 
  Attempts made by the trade unions to persuade the government 
to set discount tariffs on the use of energy holders for 
fuel-intensive industries have come to nothing. At present 
energy holders have reached 70 percent of the cost prices in the 
production of titanium, zinc, lead, and other commodities. This 
has forced the enterprises to set prices for their goods at 
levels that are higher than world prices. 
  According to the trade union leader, Kazbek Valiyev, the 
working people have appealed to the president and the Supreme 
Council to dismiss the Republic's government. 
  The collectives of the oblast's enterprises, who have 
already 
set up strike committees, have no intention of retracting from 
the demands they have put forward. If the expected changes do 
not occur in the next few days, they intend to put forward an 
initiative for the staging of an all-republican protest strike. 
  Such an appeal could be upheld in the Republic where, at 
present, 1200 enterprises are standing idle. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

