<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Warns of Dangers of Russian Population Exodus </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev Warns of Dangers of Russian Population Exodus </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206195594 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1500 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1206195594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The emigration of the Russian population from 
Kirghizia [Kyrgyzstan] is a catastrophe not only for the 
Republic but for Russia as well, which is unable to receive 
hundreds of thousands of its countrymen, President Askar Akayev 
said in Bishkek. 
  Akayev recognized that the main motives for emigration were 
socio-political. In particular, the introduction of Kirghiz as 
the state language had pushed Russians out of many professional 
spheres. He also did not deny cases of discrimination in the 
entrepreneurial sphere and displays of everyday nationalism. 
  In Akayev's view, the outflow of experts from the Republic 
is 
causing irreparable damage to the republic's economy. Whereas 
in 1990 Russians accounted for more than 21 percent of the 
population, in four years their number has decreased to 17 
percent. 

</TEXT>

