<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Examines Corruption Charges Against Ministry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Examines Corruption Charges Against Ministry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406083994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0621 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Mainayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 14 June TASS -- Kirgizia [Kyrgyzstan] has 
mustered the best forces from among its military prosecutors, 
security service officers, tax inspectors, and finances [as 
received] to look into the allegations of corruption inside the 
Defence Ministry, which appeared in the local press. 
  Reporter of one of the local newspapers charged the leaders 
of the Defence Ministry with corruption and the desire to get 
rich at the expense of the Army. The Defence Ministry responded 
by publishing a statement saying that the Kanat project, 
mentioned by the reporter, was designed to help finance the 
Republic's armed forces. 
  According to Colonel Isayev, the sale of obsolete military 
equipment within the frame of the Kanat project earned the 
ministry about four million U.S. dollars, all of which went to 
create and maintain the Republic's new army. The army is paid 
from the state budget less than one fourth of the money it needs 
to operate normally. 

</TEXT>

