<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Niyazov: No Future Without Close Ties With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Niyazov: No Future Without Close Ties With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406084694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0726 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406084694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Glazovskaya] </F>
  [Text] Ashgabat 14 June TASS -- "We cannot conceive a 
future for our selves without close cooperation with the Russian 
Federation, without mutual fraternal support in all aspects of 
policy and economy. Friendship with Russia is for us the basic 
foreign political factor, proceeding from which we determine our 
positions in international relations," President Saparmurat 
Niyazov said in a message of greetings to President Boris 
Yeltsin on Russia's Independence Day. 
  The message says that having embarked on a path of 
deep-going 
reforms the renewed democratic Russia has made it clear to the 
world that it is a great power which will not succumb to 
temporary difficulties. "I am confident that the time is not 
far away when Russia shows the world its own "economic miracle" 
and regain its might and glory," President Niyazov said. 
  The peoples of great Russia and Turkmenistan have been bound 
together by their common historical fate and deep 
inter-penetration of cultures, as well as by the common tasks 
facing them now. 
  "We know that Russia's well-being is a major component of 
our 
own independence which we value highly and of our own well-being 
both at present and in the future," Turkmenistan's president 
said. 
  Niyazov also sent a message of greetings to Viktor 
Chernomyrdin expressing satisfaction with the level of relations 
between the two countries, as well as gratitude for support 
which the Russian premier extends to Turkmenistan. 

</TEXT>

