<F P=102>   LD1406090494 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 0800 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406090494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin today left for a 
working visit to Blagoveshchensk in Amur Oblast. Before his 
departure, Boris Yeltsin gave an interview to journalists at the 
airport. In particular, he spoke about his telephone 
conversation with U.S. President Clinton a day before. 
  [Begin Yeltsin recording] We discussed several issues. 
First, the North Korean nuclear issue. And we agreed, or 
rather it was our proposal, to put forward to the Security 
Council a question about an international conference and, 
simultaneously, about sanctions -- phased-in ones. It is a very 
serious matter. So there you are. Later, Kozyrev and 
Christopher are to meet tomorrow or the day after in Brussels, 
where they are to agree the text. [end recording] 
  The presidents also discussed the question of Boris 
Yeltsin's 
visit to the United States in September this year. As for his 
visit to the Far East and Siberia, the Russian president noted 
the regions' specific features and abundance of mineral 
resources there. 
  [Begin Yeltsin recording] We have now somehow concentrated 
on 
the foreign countries in the east, and I think it is from there 
that an inflow of investment can be expected. This is something 
we are now lacking. I refer to China, Japan, and the Republic 
of Korea. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

