<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Official, Newspaper Cited on DPRK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Official, Newspaper Cited on DPRK Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM1306141794 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 11 Jun 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM1306141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [ITAR-TASS report: "North Korea: Imposition of Sanctions </F>
Is Matter of Time"] 
  [Text] The imposition of sanctions on North Korea is 
already settled and merely a matter of time. This was stated by 
Madeleine Albright, U.S. permanent representative to the United 
Nations. "We are making progress in this area at the necessary 
rate," she said. "But the main thing in this problem is to take 
the measures, and not the speed with which this is done." 
  According to her the United States will proceed with the 
imposition of sanctions on Pyongyang for its refusal to allow 
International Atomic Energy Agency inspectors access to its 
nuclear facilities, even if China refuses to cooperate in this 
sphere. At the same time Albright expressed the hope, based on 
the experience of dealings with Chinese diplomats at the United 
Nations, that "Beijing realizes that the emergence of a nuclear 
North Korea is not in its interests." 
  "A week after Washington stated that it would seek the 
imposition of economic sanctions on North Korea, the 
administration of President Bill Clinton is still working 
intensively on a plan of such actions," THE NEW YORK TIMES 
writes. 

</TEXT>

