<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Accusations Against IAEA Carry `Grain of Truth' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Accusations Against IAEA Carry `Grain of Truth' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306205294 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1920 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1306205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent F. Tavrovskiy; from the </F>
"Vesti" newscast] 
  [Text] Here is a sensational report we have received from 
the ITAR-TASS news agency today. This is what it says. The 
North Korean Foreign Ministry has stated that North Korea is to 
pull out of the International Atomic Energy Agency immediately 
and is set to pursue its independent nuclear program in the 
future. 
  [Tavrovskiy] The declaration made public by the North Korean 
Foreign Ministry says that the reason for adopting it was the 
recent decision by the International Atomic Energy Agency to 
stop technical aid to North Korea. Pyongyang confirmed that 
North Korea's membership of the Nonproliferation Treaty has been 
suspended. Moreover, North Korea is refusing to allow 
international observers to inspect its nuclear sites in the 
future. At the same time, the IAEA said that it had received no 
notification as yet from North Korea about its decision to 
resign from the agency. 
  Perhaps, after North Korea's step today, sanctions which the 
United States, Japan, and South Korea want will be inevitable. 
At the same time, Pyongyang says that if the sanctions are 
imposed, a terrible war will be waged on the Korean peninsula. 
  There is no doubt that the actions of the North Korean 
regime 
must be condemned. Nevertheless, I would like to say that South 
Africa and Israel may well have a nuclear bomb as well. It is 
quite possible that Libya and Pakistan also possess it. So when 
North Korea blames the IAEA of double-standards, its words carry 
a certain grain of truth. The best way out of the current 
situation may be the Russian proposal for an international 
conference for nuclear security in the Korean peninsula with all 
the interested parties taking part. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

