<HT>    "drsov114_a_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on Need for `Compromise' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on Need for `Compromise' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406094194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0848 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 14 Jun -- "As a result of personal efforts 
by the Russian president, Boris Yeltsin, there is a now a unique 
chance for you to make the correct choice," Andrey Kozyrev 
declared here today when opening talks with the leader of the 
Bosnian Serbs, Radovan Karadzic. According to the Russian 
Federation foreign minister, the first meeting about Bosnia 
between the foreign ministers of Russia, the United States and 
five European Union countries, which was held in Geneva on 13 
May, "created a good foundation for peace." This foundation is, 
first and foremost, "full equality of rights for the peoples of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and full equality of choice for the Bosnian 
Serbs." In the near future "We intend to attempt to hold a 
second ministerial meeting which will provide an opportunity to 
reach a very important agreement on this basis, precisely within 
this framework." 
  By opting for peace, A. Kozyrev continued, the Bosnian Serbs 
will be able to count on Russia's most resolute support. Among 
other things, Russia believes that when the territorial issue is 
decided the Serb people of Bosnia-Herzegovina should hold 49 
percent of the territory. History has decreed that although the 
Serbs form only around 33 percent of the Bosnian population, 
they are entitled to claim a large and fair slice of territory. 
When peace is restored, sanctions will be lifted, Yugoslavia 
will rejoin the "family of nations," and assistance will be 
given with the rehabilitation of the war-damaged economy. 
  In order to avoid misunderstandings, the Russian minister 
went on to say, I would also like to issue a clear warning. 
There is another option, leading to war -- unwillingness to 
accept reasonable compromises and an intention to hold on to 70 
percent of the territory which is now being held by the Bosnian 
Serb as a result of the war. If you do opt for war -- and we 
believe that this will not happen -- we must state just as 
firmly that you will not, in that case, be able to count on 
Russia. "As real friends, we only support fair play," A. Kozyrev 
stressed. "Russia will not support injustice." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40076 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov114_a_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on Russian Support </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on Russian Support </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1406085794 Paris AFP in English 0825 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1406085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 14 (AFP) -- Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev called on Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic Tuesday 
to accept the proposed partitioning of Bosnia-Hercegovina which 
he said would lead to economic aid from Russia and the end of 
sanctions. 
  "If you choose war, you will not be able to count on us for 
support," Kozyrev warned Karadzic who arrived here Monday to 
receive a literary award from the conservative Writers' Union. 
  The foreign minister said he supported granting Bosnian 
Serbs 
49.1 percent of the territory in line with the proposed peace 
plan but that 70 percent was "much too much". 
  He told Karadzic that if Bosnian Serbs accept the plan, "you 
can count on Russia's firm support," adding that it would lead 
to the lifting of sanctions against former Yugoslavia and fresh 
economic aid. 
  Karadzic stated that Bosnian Serbs were "tired" of the 
four-year conflict and that they wanted peace. 
  He thanked the Russian leadership for its support, adding: 
"We know that Russia is our friend." 
  Kozyrev reiterated his call for a second ministerial meeting 
to pursue the efforts launched at the first conference held in 
Geneva in May. 
  "This conference lead to the recognition of equal rights for 
all peoples of Bosnia," Kozyrev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40077 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov114_a_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-114 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Warns of Continuing War </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Warns of Continuing War </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306205594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2038 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1306205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 13 (TANJUG) -- President of the Bosnian 
Serb republic Radovan Karadzic has warned that the war in Bosnia 
might continue if totally unacceptable maps are offered. 
  Karadzic is in Moscow to receive the Mikhail Sholokov prize 
for literature which has been awarded to him by the Association 
of Russian Writers. 
  In a statement to reporters at Moscow airport upon his 
arrival on Monday, Karadzic said that no-one can expect Bosnian 
Serbs to accept something in whose creation they did not take 
part, including maps which do not take into consideration the 
actual situation in the field, without respect for the 
historical factors and especially the vital interests of the 
Serb people. 
  Under the plan of the contact group which consists of 
representatives of the United States, Russia, and the European 
Union, the territory of the former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia- 
Herzegovina will be divided into two parts, 51 percent for the 
Moslem-Croat federation and 49 percent for the Serb republic. 
  Some U.S. circles are behind the beginning of the Bosnian 
war 
and its prolonging, Karadzic said, emphasizing that he was not 
blaming the entire U.S. administration for this. 
  Pointing out that the Moslem-Croat federation in Bosnia- 
Herzegovina was created without the participation of Bosnian 
Serbs, Karadzic underscored that the federation was created only 
by respecting the military factor, in the sense of forming an 
anti-Serb coalition. 
  Representatives of Bosnian Croats and Moslems and Croatia 
signed a preliminary agreement in Washington on March 1, under 
strong pressure from the U.S., on the forming of a federation of 
the two peoples in the territory of Bosnia-Herzegovina which 
would later enter into a confederation with Croatia. 
  Political analysts believe that Washington is again trying 
to 
isolate Bosnian Serbs with this initiative and pressure them 
into making territorial concessions more easily at the 
conference table. 
  Despite the embargo, Moslems and Croats in Bosnia are arming 
themselves, so that the decision adopted by the House of 
Representatives of U.S. Congress last week to exempt Moslems 
from the embargo on arms sales to former Yugoslavia actually has 
no major significance. 
  I would like such a decision to be adopted, because in that 
case I expect Russia would lift the sanctions against 
Yugoslavia, Karadzic said. 
  The United Nations Security Council imposed an embargo on 
arms sales to all republics of the former Yugoslav federation in 
the autumn of 1991, and two years ago, also comprehensive and 
tough sanctions against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, 
unjustly accusing it of having the greatest responsibility for 
the outbreak of the civil war in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Karadzic concluded that Moslems in Bosnia-Herzegovina are 
not 
interested in the establishment of peace, but urge the war 
option, because they have the support of the United States. 
  The Bosnian Serb president said that he expected he would 
meet with Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and other ministry 
officials. He expressed hope that he would meet also with Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and Russian Federation President 
Boris Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

