<H3> <TI>   Roundtable Conference Views Collective Security Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundtable Conference Views Collective Security Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406095394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0913 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 14 TASS--"Strange as it may seem, 
collective security problems assumed greater importance after 
the ending of the Cold War", said Sergey Yushenkov, chairman of 
the Defence Committee in the State Duma. He inaugurated on 
Tuesday a round-table conference on "Topical Problems of 
Collective Security in Europe". 
  "We all wish to make Europe more secure and stamp out 
military conflicts that flared up in the territory of the former 
USSR", he said. 
  Participants in the "round-table conference", among them 
British MPs, noted that certain caution had become apparent in 
relations between Russia and NATO of late. Russia and the West 
have not agreed on any legal principles of the stay of Russian 
troops in CIS countries, Russian expert Aleksandr Nikitin 
pointed out. He believes a draft concept of collective security 
of the CIS countries should be discussed by a meeting of the 
State Duma. This concept should also be discussed with NATO 
representatives so they could rightly understand the concept. 
  Member of the British parliament Bruce George said the 
Partnership for Peace programme is just an initial step in the 
establishment of closer relations between Russia and NATO. This 
is also an attempt to prevent rapid integration of East European 
countries in NATO to which Russia may react negatively. 
Russia's joining in the Partnership for Peace programme will 
lead to greater mutual knowledge and confidence. The 
integration process can then be embarked upon, Bruce George said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

