<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev To Meet Slavs; Hopes To Resolve Migration `Headache' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev To Meet Slavs; Hopes To Resolve Migration `Headache' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406085594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0758 GMT 14 jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406085594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Mainayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 14 June TASS -- "It's no ethnic Chernobyl 
(nuclear disaster) yet, but `peak hour'", thus President of 
Kirghizia [Kyrgyzstan] Asker Akayev graphically assessed the 
state of current migration process from the republic. Akayev 
intends to find a way out of the prevailing situation during his 
meeting today with representatives of the Slav diaspora in 
Kirghizia. 
  At present the republic's over four million population 
consists of 56.5 per cent native Kirghizs, but the people of 
Russian, Ukrainian and Belarussian nationalities account for 
21.1 per cent. 
  Four years ago there were 905.4 thousand Russian-speaking 
people living in Kirghizia. Now this diaspora has shrunk to 
almost 170 thousand. The process of migration is gathering 
momentum everyday. 
  According to the president, this process can be stopped only 
by giving official status to the Russian language, and 
introducing duel citizenship. But both alternatives run 
contrary to the Constitution of Kirghizia. The republic's 
present parliament has more than once demonstrated that it does 
not intend to amend or change the fundamental law. How to find 
a compromise, stop migration, without arousing a wave of 
nationalism, this is what is causing the present "headache" to 
President Akayev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40130 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov114_s_94001" </HT>


