<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin on Talk With Clinton, Far East Tour </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin on Talk With Clinton, Far East Tour </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406055694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0547 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406055694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 14 TASS -- President Boris Yeltsin, 
before departure for Blagoveshchensk by air, told journalists on 
Tuesday that an understanding to "link the convocation of an 
international conference and the application of possible 
stage-by-stage sanctions against North Korea" had been reached 
during his long conversation with President Clinton on Monday 
night. 
  Apart from discussing the North Korean nuclear issue, the 
two 
presidents also examined some aspects of Boris Yeltsin's likely 
official visit to America in autumn. "Judging by the prospective 
time-frame, the trip will turn out well. Besides, it is planned 
that I will deliver a programmatic address at the U.N. General 
Assembly", Yeltsin remarked. 
  In this connection, Yeltsin said that Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev and U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher are to meet in Brussels on June 15-16 to specify 
details of the forthcoming visit. 
  As far as the tour of Blagoveshchensk and the Republic of 
Tuva is concerned, Yeltsin voiced hope that foreign investments 
would be drawn to those areas, primarily from China, Japan, 
North and South Korea. "This may help those regions in earnest," 
he emphasised. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

