<DATE1>  13 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discuss DPRK Nuclear Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discuss DPRK Nuclear Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306195294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1916 
GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1306195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 13 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- A telephone 
conversation took place today between Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton. 
  According to the report received by ITAR-TASS from the 
Russian president's press office, the presidents continued their 
discussion of the situation that has developed around the North 
Korean nuclear problem and possible steps for its political 
resolution. In connection with this, Boris Yeltsin and Bill 
Clinton exchanged opinions on the UN Security Council resolution 
that is being prepared, and which should give equal weight to 
the ideas of both possible sanctions and an international 
conference to resolve the problems of the Korean peninsula. The 
presidents agreed to instruct Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev and U.S Secretary of State Warren Christopher to 
continue close consultations on these issues. 

</TEXT>

