<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Omanidze Returns From Exile, Politics on Agenda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Omanidze Returns From Exile, Politics on Agenda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206151894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1449 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206151894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi June 12 -- Murman Omanidze, who was the 
foreign minister in the Zviad Gamsakhurdia government, has 
returned home after a two-year exile and is now taking part in 
the elections of a deputy to the parliament from the Rustavi 
constituency. The new deputy will replace Zhiuli Shartava, 
chairman of the council of ministers of the autonomous republic, 
who died a tragic death in Abkhazia. 
  At first nine candidates were vying for the seat in 
parliament. Later three candidates withdrew from the electoral 
campaign, and two of them urged the electors to vote for Murman 
Omanidze. 
  Omanidze, 56, is in perfect health. In younger years he 
actively practiced sports and got the title of master of sports 
for unarmed self-defence. Aside from it, he showed a special 
gift for business, when he was still a student of the law 
department of Tbilisi university. Now he is vice president and 
executive director of the joint Austrian-Finnish firm Stellar 
with the turnover of hundreds of millions of U.S. dollars and 
tens of billions of roubles. 
  Once speaking at a press conference, Omanidze said that if 
he 
came to power, he would make Georgia into a flourishing country 
in two to three years. He, a wealthy man with numerous 
connections in the business circles of Russia and other 
countries and without nationalistic prejudices, is giving 
priority to economic interests. 
  According to reliable sources close to the Georgian 
leadership, if Murman Omanidze is elected deputy to the Georgian 
parliament, he may soon become prime minister of the republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

