<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Supports Phased Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia Supports Phased Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1406114194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1127 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1406114194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, June 14 (YONHAP) -- Russia would agree to 
phased sanctions against North Korea if Pyongyang seeks to 
withdraw from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT), Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin said on Tuesday. 
  In an airport press conference prior to his departure for a 
local tour, Yeltsin said, "If North Korea tries to push ahead 
with its withdrawal from the NPT, Russia would convene an 
emergency international meeting and agree to phased sanctions 
against Pyongyang." 
  He said he had a telephone conversation with U.S. President 
Bill Clinton Monday on the North Korean nuclear question and 
Korean situation. 
  Russian televisions and radios reported that in their 
telephone talks, it was agreed that President Yeltsin would make 
an official visit to the United States in coming autumn. 
  One of the major topics of the Yeltsin-Clinton meeting would 
be the North Korean nuclear question in addition to the issue of 
bilateral economic cooperation, they said. 
  Meanwhile, an ITAR-TASS report said a senior Chinese Defense 
Ministry official on Monday gave a strong-worded message to Choe 
Kwang, chief of the General Staff of the North Korean People's 
Army, that North Korea should not depart from its being a 
non-nuclear country. 

</TEXT>

