<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on Readiness for Partnership for Peace, NATO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on Readiness for Partnership for Peace, NATO </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406122894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1037 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Kozlov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 14 Jun -- Russia is prepared in the near 
future to sign a framework document of the Partnership for Peace 
initiative together with a program of full-scale cooperation 
with NATO. An ITAR-TASS correspondent was told this here today 
by Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev at the conclusion of 
talks with Mikhail Popov, his Moldovan counterpart. From 
Moscow's point of view, the Russian minister added, as far as 
deciding this particular question was concerned, it might be a 
matter of days, or even hours, rather than weeks. 
  Now, said Kozyrev, everything depends on how fast we receive 
a reply signal from Brussels to activate both the framework 
document and the Russia-NATO program, whose main principles were 
presented to the NATO leadership by Russian Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev. According to Kozyrev, the program of cooperation 
with NATO is a very full of documents, which reflects Russia's 
importance in international affairs and the specific nature of 
its relations with the NATO, "without any mutual vetoes or 
surprises." 
  The Moldovan minister told the ITAR-TASS correspondent that 
his country, which signed the framework document in March of 
this year, also plans to submit to NATO in the near future a 
program of individual cooperation. Talking about the advantages 
Moldova will gain from participating in the Partnership for 
Peace programme, Popov noted in particular that if the republic 
finds itself under threat from outside, it will be able to hold 
consultations with NATO the in the interest of strengthening 
stability and national security. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

