<DOCNO> FBIS4-40162 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov115_a_94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, Moldova's Popov Discuss Army Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev, Moldova's Popov Discuss Army Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406144094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1332 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406144094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow realizes the basic necessity to withdraw 
Russia's 14th Army from Moldova. There is no need to 
procrastinate this process, said Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev 
on Tuesday, upon conclusion of talks with his Moldovan 
counterpart, Mikhail Popov. 
  In answer to a question from Interfax Kozyrev said: "Russia 
clearly understands that there must be no foreign troops in a 
sovereign state. However it's not easy to prepare an organized 
withdrawal of the 14th Army. This process will take time." 
  According to him, "it's useless to speak about serious 
differences in the two sides' approaches to the times of 
withdrawal." "Both Russia and Moldova realize perfectly well the 
complexity of this issue, to which neither side has a clear 
answer. It's gratifying that no one has tried to tackle this 
problem unilaterally," Kozyrev noted. 
  For his part, Popov said that the presence of the 14th Army 
in Trans-Dniestria [Transdniester] is "the most inconvenient 
part of the Soviet legacy in relations between Russia and 
Moldova." "We do not blame Russia for the resulting situation," 
he stressed. 
  The head of Moldovan diplomacy said he hopes that the 
concrete times of withdrawal will be agreed upon during the next 
round of bilateral talks planned for July. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

