<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shakhray Calls For New CIS Confederation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shakhray Calls For New CIS Confederation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406145194 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1200 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] At the Diplomatic Academy in Moscow today, the first 
roundtable was held under the aegis of the Russian Unity and 
Accord party. Participating were representatives of the 
administrations of the CIS countries, politicians, and 
diplomats. The prospects for Eurasian integration were the 
subject of discussion. 
  Speaking at the meeting, Deputy Prime Minister Sergey 
Shakhray stressed that the time had come to think about making 
the CIS into a confederation of an EEC type. That would not 
mean the reinstatement of the former USSR. In the EAU--short 
for Euro-Asian union--every state will be sovereign and 
independent. However, there is an obstacle in the way, Shakhray 
said; this is the continuing rise of nationalism in the 
countries of the CIS, including Great Russian nationalism. He 
said the key to solving the problem is the establishment of 
genuine federalism and local self-administration. 
  Marat Shizhirin, deputy head of the Kazakh president's 
administration, spoke about the mechanisms for the formation of 
the EAU today. In order to enter the EAU, it will be necessary 
to hold a referendum or to adopt a decision at the level of a 
country's parliament. At the same time, the alliance will not 
allow associate membership. The observation of interstate 
agreements will be an absolute part of the EAU code. The 
territorial integrity of the member states of the alliance will 
be rigidly observed. The main condition for membership in the 
EAU is the halting of combat actions. All this will create a 
new impetus for rapprochement of the former USSR's republics, 
both from a political and economic point of view, the speakers 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40172 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov115_a_94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Praises Eurasian Union </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Praises Eurasian Union </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406202294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1759 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During the Perspectives for Euro-Asian Integration 
round-table discussion in Moscow today Russian Vice Premier 
Sergey Shakhray highly appraised the initiative on establishment 
of the Euro-Asian Union put forward by Kazakh President 
Nursultan Nazarbayev. 
  Shakhray said that the matter was not whether to unite or 
not 
but how to unite. 
  Shakhray stressed that integration must be carried out in a 
civilized way, equitably and voluntarily, preserving the 
political sovereignty of the countries involved. Otherwise, he 
said, the result could be the use of force. 
  Shakhray said that the issue of uniting and restoring 
economic and other ties was now a factor of political stability 
in all CIS states, including Russia. 
  "The forms and the title of the new integration can vary," 
Shakhray said. He added that the CIS will be becoming more and 
more efficient and friendship with Russia will be the victor at 
the presidential elections in Belarus and Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

