<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intelligence Chief: Service Still Tops Despite Hard Times </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intelligence Chief: Service Still Tops Despite Hard Times </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406141994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1345 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Olga Semenova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 14 TASS -- Despite all the reshuffling 
and financial difficulties, the Russian intelligence remains 
among the four best secret services in the world which also 
include the CIA, the Israeli Mossad and the British secret 
service. "We have always been in the league and, I hope, will 
remain there", first deputy director of the Russian Foreign 
Intelligence Service (SVR) Vyacheslav Trubnikov told TASS on 
Tuesday. 
  He did not specify who occupies which place among the four, 
but said that hardly any of the secret services would have 
succeeded to maintain the leading positions had they been in the 
same financial plight as the SVR. 
  "I am sure that had the personnel of our `competitors' been 
in the same conditions as the Russian intelligence is facing, 
hardly many of them would have tolerated that. And our men do 
serve and will serve", Trubnikov said. 
  The Foreign Intelligence Service which appeared after the 
collapse of the notorious KGB is no longer engaged in political 
persecutions. According to Trubnikov, "intelligence ceased to 
be a semi-state and semi-(communist) party body which it was in 
the times of the KGB". It no longer works for any political 
party, advocates no ideology, acts independently and according 
to law and is controlled by the legislative and executive 
authorities. 
  The task of the intelligence is to monitor and assess 
threats 
to Russian national interests. "In general the tendencies in 
world development are favourable for our country, however, the 
spectrum of threats remains rather wide", Trubnikov said and 
added that the major threat at present is the "hot spots" on the 
Russian borders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40184 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov115_b_94006" </HT>


