<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foton Satellite Launched From Plesetsk Cosmodrome </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foton Satellite Launched From Plesetsk Cosmodrome </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406201294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1759 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's air and space forces (ASP) launched a Foton 
satellite with the Soyuz carrier rocket from the Plesetsk space 
site at 20:00 Moscow time. 
  The Foton satellite which weighs 6,200 kg will carry out a 
series of material processing experiments. The program will 
last 18 days plus one reserve day. The satellite carries 700 kg 
of research equipment. Experiments were developed at the 
experimental engineering office in Moscow. 
  The launch was attended by members of the former Russian 
royal family, designers of space technologies and 
representatives of the European space agency. 
  The program envisages the launch of another Foton satellite. 
The first Foton satellite was launched on April 16 1985. Eight 
Fotons have so far been launched. The last launch took place on 
October 8 1992. 

</TEXT>

