<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Arrives in Blagoveshchensk; Tours Amur Oblast </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Arrives in Blagoveshchensk; Tours Amur Oblast </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Visits Shipbuilding Plant </H4>

<F P=102> LD1506054594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0523 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506054594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Tamara Zamyatina and </F>
Vladimir Konoplitsky] 
  [Text] Blagoveshchensk June 15 TASS -- President Boris 
Yeltsin on Wednesday visited the Blagoveshchensk shipbuilding 
plant. The workers and managerial personnel of the plant told 
Yeltsin about a variety of problems, the main of which is to 
find customers for the manufacture of fishing seiners. The 
president of russian and Economics Minister Aleksandr Shokhin 
made entries in the visitors' book promising the shipbuilders to 
promote a solution to the problem. 
  Shipbuilders told ITAR-TASS that they have not been 
receiving 
wages since February. Customers -- the fishery enterprises all 
over Far East, acutely need the plant's products but 
nevertheless are unable to pay for the completed seiners. This 
is why the plant managament sends workers on forced leaves. 
With the plant personnel numbering 1,300, the managament has 
already sent 1,000 shipbuilders on leave in June. 
  As of now, the default of payment for completed and building 
ships amount to 8,000 million roubles. 
  The defence and interior ministries owe about 1,500 million 
roubles to the plant. 
  The president toured a small fishing seiner of the latest 
make and visited the shipbuilding shop. 
  During a meeting with the management of the plant, Boris 
Yeltsin once again promised to give assistance in the search for 
customers for large fishing seiners and suggested making small 
boats, which farmers need, on direct, non-state orders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

