<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Leader on </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Leader on </PHRASE></F></HT>


<TEXT>
Heavy   Casualties in Groznyy 

<F P=102> LD1406124094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1045 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 14 Jun -- Speaking on behalf of the Chechen 
government of popular trust, its leader Yaragi Mamodayev today 
expressed his condolences to compatriots over the tragic events 
in Groznyy. Commenting on the latest developments to an 
ITAR-TASS correspondent, he said: "This bloodshed shows that the 
process of self-annihilation of the Chechen people, against 
which our government has been warning everyone for a whole year, 
is exacerbating." Yaragi Mamodayev cited as evidence of this 
the fact that forces which, until quite recently, could in 
effect have been described as allies, for one reason or another 
clashed in Groznyy on 13 June. 
  According to Yaragi Mamodayev, more people have been killed 
in Chechnya since the first bloody conflict in June last year 
than in the open war in former Yugoslavia. The number of 
casualties in yesterday's tragedy was also several times higher 
than official figures suggest. 
  It is precisely because each day and each hour of the 
confrontation is claiming more human lives that our government 
once again urges the present Chechen leadership to seek 
reconciliation, not just in order to ensure peace for our 
compatriots, but for the sake of the very future of the Chechen 
people, Yaragi Mamodayev stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40205 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov115_d_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Says Hundreds Killed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Says Hundreds Killed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506134194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1221 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Chechen opposition stated that from 180 to 300 
people had been killed as a result of the armed clashes in 
Grozny last Sunday. 
  The Chechen Interim Council, which opposites [as received] 
to 
Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev said that innocent people had 
suffered during these clashes, including women and children. 
  Official authorities in Groznyy refuted this information 
saying that no more than ten people had been killed and no more 
than sixty wounded. 
  The armed clashes between government forces and the militant 
group of Ruslan Labazanov took place in a district of Groznyy. 
The clashes followed the order to disarm illegal armed 
formations in Chechnya issued by Chechen Military Commander 
Sultan Geliskhanov. 
  The opposition headquarters refuted the government statement 
that a wide-scale and decisive struggle against crime had begun 
in the republic. The opposition said that the Chechen 
leadership had started the bloodshed in order to eliminate the 
members of the armed group whom it had considered as supporters 
not so long ago. 
  The Interim Council said that opposition activist Labazanov 
was a witness to many criminal actions by the leadership. That 
is why the decision was taken to kill him, an opposition 
representative, who did not want his name to be revealed, went 
on to say. 
  Labazanov has managed to flee with a group of militants. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

