<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hryb Praises CIS, Money Merger at News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hryb Praises CIS, Money Merger at News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1506074394 Minsk NARODNAYA GAZETA in Belarusian 11-13 Jun 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> WS1506074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk NARODNAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Belarusian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aleh Hrusdzilovich on a news conference by </F>
Belarusian Supreme Soviet Chairman Myacheslaw Hryb; place and 
date not given: "The CIS Has Prospects. Stanislaw Bahdankevich 
Does Not Violate Laws"] 
  [Text] CIS Executive Secretary Ivan Karatchenya and 
Belarusian Supreme Soviet Chairman Myacheslaw Hryb, who returned 
from St. Petersburg, where they participated in the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly, organized a news conference for 
journalists. 
  Myacheslaw Hryb opened the press conference with a joke 
saying that the journalists were so occupied with the 
presidential race that they almost forgot about the Supreme 
Soviet chairman. Myacheslaw Hryb assessed the agreements signed 
in St. Petersburg and answered a range of questions. The 
Supreme Soviet chairman was convinced that interest in him and 
his personal opinions on some pressing issues of our life did 
not decrease. We paid attention to five key questions which 
Myacheslaw Hryb had to answer: on CIS prospects, on the 
initiative -- regarding the creation of the Eurasian union -- of 
the Kazakhstani President Nursultan Nazarbayev, on unexpected 
changes in prices for bread, and on National Bank Chairman 
Stanislaw Bahdankevich's recent moves. 
  "Our St. Petersburg meeting was very fruitful. In my 
opinion, work aimed at strengthening the CIS has sense, and the 
CIS has prospects," is how Supreme Soviet chairman answered the 
first question. Following are his words regarding Nazarbayev's 
initiative: "The president of Kazakhstan proposes two versions 
of the so-called Eurasian union -- mild and tough -- with which 
we should acquaint our society. What I like in this proposal is 
that it plans to set a union of states with equal rights. 
Under these conditions, the obligations of the allies would be 
more specified because the union does not foresee associate 
membership. In my opinion, this proposal does not run counter 
to the CIS. However, I would like to emphasize that the 
attitude of the CIS leaders toward this initiative is different. 
  "I think that we should not change the text of the 
Constitution," stated Myacheslaw Hryb regarding the monetary 
merger. He confirmed his earlier position which is that the 
state requires a tough Constitution because only such a 
constitution can be respected. Myacheslaw Hryb said that when he 
spoke earlier with president Yeltsin, they agreed that the 
fifth, and, probably, the eighth clauses of the agreement could 
be redrafted. However, the text of the agreement was submitted 
to Deputy Prime Minister Shokhin and work halted for a while. 
  As for the unexpected changes in prices for bread and some 
other foodstuffs, Myacheslaw Hryb said: "The government adopted 
this decision when I was in St. Petersburg. My personal opinion 
is that currently we cannot do without state management of the 
economy. The majority of enterprises are state-owned but the 
state cannot even affect the prices for products of these 
enterprises." 
  "We exercised juridical expertise regarding recent decisions 
adopted by the National Bank. It confirmed that everything was 
done within the limits of competence," said the Supreme Soviet 
chairman in reply to the last question. "As for Stanislaw 
Bahdankevich who adopted presidential candidate Stanislaw 
Shushkevich's proposal to head his `shadow' cabinet, this is his 
personal affair. By the way, former Interior Minister Yladzimir 
Yahoraw also joined the Shushkevich team and became his campaign 
manager. Well, this is their personal position." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

