<DOCNO> FBIS4-40227 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov115_e_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-115 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Cooperation Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Cooperation Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406172994 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1600 
GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1406172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk arrived in 
Luxembourg today on a one-day working visit, following meetings 
there on Monday [13 June] and Tuesday of the European Union's 
Council of Foreign Ministers. Also today, he signed an 
agreement on partnership and cooperation between Ukraine and the 
European Union. 
  The document confirms that the EEC member-states will 
support 
Ukraine as a sovereign and independent state within its existing 
borders. The agreement lays down the principles of, and a 
mechanism for, a permanent political dialogue between Ukraine 
and the EEC and systems of periodic consultations at different 
levels on the entire range of political, economic, cultural, and 
other issues. 
  The agreement also provides a qualitatively new basis for 
economic relations between Ukraine and the European Union on 
market economy principles. The sides will grant each other most 
favored nation status in trade, and will lift import 
restrictions with regard to trade agreements in coal, metal, and 
nuclear materials. Ukraine will also be able to sell its textile 
products on the European market. 
  The sides urge employers to lift discriminatory restrictions 
on employment of the partner country's citizens and ensure that 
the citizens' pension rights are preserved. 
  National terms are granted to European Union companies 
functioning on Ukrainian territory and with regard to access of 
trade ships to each side's ports. 
  The Ukraine and Luxembourg foreign ministers signed an air 
transport agreement. 
  The Chernobyl aid package to ensure complete shutdown of 
this 
nuclear plant and the safety of others will be finally agreed 
before the G-7 Summit in Naples. Leonid Kravchuk confirmed 
Kiev's consent to shut down the Chernobyl reactors if the 
international community assists Ukraine in this matter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

