<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Special Status' for Russia in NATO Partnership Opposed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Special Status' for Russia in NATO Partnership Opposed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406141594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1332 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine does not support Russia's intention to seek 
a special status within the framework of NATO' Partnership for 
Peace program, the chief of the Ukrainian Foreign Ministry's 
political analysis department, Igor Kharchenko, told IF. 
  In reply to a question from the INTERFAX-Ukraine news agency 
Kharchenko said that "practically all member-countries were 
against any advantages being granted to any country involved in 
that program, contrary to statements by Russian politicians that 
Russia's opportunities were far wider than those of other 
countries." 
  Kharchenko said that Russia's relations with NATO were 
crucial to European security. 
  The Ukrainian Foreign Ministry official said that Ukraine 
was 
conducting "a consistent policy in order to take a decent place 
in the system of collective European security and not to drift 
either eastwards or westwards." 

</TEXT>

