<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Considered State Language To Slow Emigration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Considered State Language To Slow Emigration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406142694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1332 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian language will be considered as a state 
one in Kyrgyzstan's regions mostly populated by the 
Russian-speaking population, Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev 
stated in his decree, which he read out during a meeting with 
the Slav community on Tuesday [14 June] in Bishkek. 
  Akayev said the decree had been issued in order to prevent 
further growth in the number of the Russian-speaking people 
emigrating from Kyrgyzstan. 
  The Kyrgyz Government will try to ensure equal 
representation 
of the Slav community in the state and local administration. 
  The decree also provides for guaranteed representation of 
the 
ethnic minorities in all state power bodies. Within a month the 
Kyrgyz Foreign Ministry will work out proposals on the 
acquisition of citizenship for Russian-speaking inhabitants of 
Kyrgyzstan leaving for Russia and for those willing to come back 
to Kyrgyzstan from Russia. The proposals will be coordinated 
with the Russian party. 
  The Kyrgyz Interior Ministry and the National Security 
Committee will strengthen their struggle against nationalism. 
  Akayev suggested that the migration by the Russian-speaking 
population was causing large damage to the potential of 
Kyrgyzstan on the whole. He emphasized that increasing 
migration was due to the problems with the language, 
insufficient representation in the state bodies and other 
official structures and the display of nationalism in everyday 
life. 
  Akayev announced that he had prepared one more letter to 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin asking Russia to help Kyrgyzstan 
to resolve the economic problems. Akayev stressed that these 
issues must be settled urgently if Russia was interested in 
ensuring the position of Russians living in Kyrgyzstan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40234 </DOCNO>
