<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Masol Running for Premiership To Reverse Economic Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Masol Running for Premiership To Reverse Economic Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1406140994 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1200 GMT 14 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1406140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev [no dateline as received] -- Candidate for the 
post of Ukraine's prime minister, people's deputy Vitaliy Masol, 
said in an exclusive interview for UNIAN during a break in the 
session that he was doubtful as to his own need to accept the 
possible appointment. "It would not add to the image, and in a 
while there will be a lot of ruckus and I will be blamed for all 
sins." Masol believes economic management over the past two 
years has led to a great many irreparable losses. He stressed 
that his only motive was "being unable to remain on the 
sidelines after the Kuchma government has made, alas, so many 
ill-considered moves." Masol said he had seen the report by 
Supreme Council Chairman Oleksandr Moroz, who will present his 
proposals on overcoming Ukraine's economic crisis at the 
parliament session on 15 June. He denied having drawn up 
Moroz's "main guidelines" himself, but said that a lot of it had 
been borrowed by the speaker from Masol's own book. 

</TEXT>

